You are working in /tmp/sv-8f79cddec62e46198c3b8a62eb85261e/ShipmentTracker which is a Blazor Web App solution with two projects:
- ShipmentTracker (server) at ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker/
- ShipmentTracker.Client (WASM) at ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/

The app uses InteractiveAuto render mode and Individual accounts authentication (ASP.NET Core Identity with SQLite). The template has already been scaffolded with `dotnet new blazor -int Auto -au Individual`.

Your task: Add shipment tracking features for a logistics company. Please implement ALL of the following:

## 1. Shared Models (create a new ShipmentTracker.Shared class library project)

Create a shared project `ShipmentTracker.Shared` so both server and client can reference the same models.

File: `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Shared/ShipmentTracker.Shared.csproj`
```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <TargetFramework>net9.0</TargetFramework>
    <ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>
    <Nullable>enable</Nullable>
  </PropertyGroup>
</Project>
```

File: `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Shared/Shipment.cs`
```csharp
namespace ShipmentTracker.Shared;

public class Shipment
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string TrackingNumber { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Origin { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public string Destination { get; set; } = string.Empty;
    public ShipmentStatus Status { get; set; }
    public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; }
    public DateTime? EstimatedDelivery { get; set; }
    public string? CustomerEmail { get; set; }
    public string? Notes { get; set; }
}

public enum ShipmentStatus
{
    Pending,
    PickedUp,
    InTransit,
    OutForDelivery,
    Delivered,
    Delayed
}
```

Add the Shared project to the solution file, and add project references from both ShipmentTracker and ShipmentTracker.Client to ShipmentTracker.Shared.

## 2. Database (server project)

Edit `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker/Data/ApplicationDbContext.cs` to add:
```csharp
using ShipmentTracker.Shared;
// ... existing code
public DbSet<Shipment> Shipments => Set<Shipment>();
```

## 3. API Endpoints (server project)

Create `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker/Endpoints/ShipmentEndpoints.cs`:
- Map minimal API endpoints under `/api/shipments`
- GET `/api/shipments` - returns all shipments (requires auth, for dispatchers)
- GET `/api/shipments/track/{trackingNumber}` - returns single shipment by tracking number (requires auth, for customers)
- POST `/api/shipments` - creates a new shipment (requires auth)
- PUT `/api/shipments/{id}` - updates shipment status (requires auth)

Use `[Authorize]` attribute or `.RequireAuthorization()` on all endpoints.

## 4. Seed Data (server project)

In Program.cs, after building the app, add code to seed the database with sample shipments if none exist. Use `app.Services.CreateScope()` to get the DbContext and add ~5 sample shipments with various statuses.

## 5. Client Pages (Client project)

### Dispatcher Dashboard - `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/Pages/Dispatcher.razor`
- Route: `/dispatcher`
- Requires authorization
- Shows a table of all shipments with columns: Tracking #, Origin, Destination, Status, Est. Delivery
- Has a dropdown filter by status
- Has a button to add a new shipment (shows inline form)
- Has buttons per row to update status
- Uses `@rendermode InteractiveAuto`

### Customer Tracking - `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/Pages/TrackShipment.razor`
- Route: `/track`
- Requires authorization
- Has a text input for tracking number and a "Track" button
- Displays shipment details: origin, destination, current status, estimated delivery
- Shows a visual progress indicator for the shipment status
- Uses `@rendermode InteractiveAuto`

## 6. Register HttpClient in Client project

In `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/Program.cs`, register `HttpClient` with the base address from the hosting environment. Use:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri(builder.HostEnvironment.BaseAddress) });
```

Also register it in the server project's Program.cs for prerendering:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpClient();
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => {
    var factory = sp.GetRequiredService<IHttpClientFactory>();
    var client = factory.CreateClient();
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://localhost");  
    return client;
});
```

Actually, a better pattern for prerendering: register a server-side service that the pages can use during prerender. But the simplest approach for Auto mode is to use HttpClient and configure the base address. For prerendering to work, let's use `IHttpClientFactory`:

In server Program.cs add:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpClient("ServerAPI", client => client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://localhost:5001"));
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => sp.GetRequiredService<IHttpClientFactory>().CreateClient("ServerAPI"));
```

Wait, actually the cleanest pattern: On the server, use the actual DbContext directly via a service interface. But since we want the Client project pages to work in both server prerender AND WASM mode, we should use HttpClient consistently.

For the server project, register HttpClient with the app's own base address (for prerendering of WASM components). But actually it's simpler: just handle the prerendering gracefully. Let me use this pattern:

In **ShipmentTracker.Client/Program.cs**:
```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.WebAssembly.Hosting;

namespace ShipmentTracker.Client;

public class Program
{
    public static async Task Main(string[] args)
    {
        var builder = WebAssemblyHostBuilder.CreateDefault(args);
        builder.Services.AddAuthorizationCore();
        builder.Services.AddCascadingAuthenticationState();
        builder.Services.AddAuthenticationStateDeserialization();
        builder.Services.AddScoped(sp => new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri(builder.HostEnvironment.BaseAddress) });
        await builder.Build().RunAsync();
    }
}
```

In **ShipmentTracker/Program.cs** (server), add before `var app = builder.Build();`:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddHttpClient();
```

And in the server for prerendering, since the WASM components use HttpClient, we need to provide one that points back to the server. The best way: use `IHttpClientFactory` and also add a named/default client. Actually the template's prerender will just use the DI container on the server side. Let's do this:

```csharp
// In server Program.cs, add:
builder.Services.AddScoped(sp =>
{
    var navigationManager = sp.GetService<Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.NavigationManager>();
    var baseAddress = navigationManager?.BaseUri ?? "https://localhost";
    return new HttpClient { BaseAddress = new Uri(baseAddress) };
});
```

This way during prerender on the server, the HttpClient gets the correct base address from NavigationManager.

## 7. Update NavMenu

Edit `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker/Components/Layout/NavMenu.razor` to replace the Counter and Weather links with:
- Dispatcher Dashboard (href="dispatcher") - inside AuthorizeView/Authorized
- Track Shipment (href="track") - inside AuthorizeView/Authorized

Keep Home link. Remove counter and weather links. Keep the existing auth links.

## 8. Update _Imports.razor in Client

Add `@using ShipmentTracker.Shared` to `ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker.Client/_Imports.razor`

## 9. Create EF Migration

After all changes, run:
```bash
cd /tmp/sv-8f79cddec62e46198c3b8a62eb85261e/ShipmentTracker/ShipmentTracker
dotnet ef migrations add AddShipments
```

If `dotnet-ef` is not installed, install it first:
```bash
dotnet tool install --global dotnet-ef
```

## 10. Build and verify

Run `dotnet build` on the solution to ensure everything compiles.

## Important implementation details:
- The Client pages should use `@attribute [Authorize]` to require authentication
- The Client pages should inject `HttpClient` and call the API endpoints
- Use `@rendermode InteractiveAuto` on the page components
- Add proper null checks and loading states
- The server's API endpoints should use `app.MapGroup("/api/shipments")` pattern

Please implement all of this. Create all necessary files and edit existing ones. Make sure it builds successfully at the end.

